Happy day of El Grito, the day of Independence of Mexico! Not only is it a day to celebrate Mexico but also, it’s a day to celebrate @lacasademamapdx 2nd anniversary!

La Casa de Mamá was started by Miriam Carrera, on this very day at the Portland El Grito event in 2021. It is a Mexican panaderia that has become a popular pop-up in the Portland metro area. 

It is focused on creating Mexican favorites such as conchas and champurrado, but with a vegan twist. They also focus on creating a welcoming space that is meant for everyone.

Every part of La Casa de Mamá is inspired by Miriam’s mother. From the recipes to the community that her mother would create through food.

A special note from La Casa de Mamá:

“Our family is incredibly grateful for the support we have received from the local community and are excited to continue learning and growing.” -La Casa de Mamá

¡Viva México! ¡Viva la independencia!

#elgrito #vivamexico #vivaméxico #veganmexicanfood #veganmexican #pdxvegan #portlandvegan #pdxfoodie #portlandfoodie #pdxeats #portlandeats #veganmexicana

@remedycoffeeshop is a for the planet coffee shop in York, England that is a must if you’re in town. It was one of my spots I visited while in York!

Every part of the process from how they roast their coffee to how it is transported and served is as carbon neutral as possible. If you want anything to go they use edible and compostable cups and boxes.

But not only are they doing their part for the planet, the coffee is delicious and they have great sweet baked goods such as babkas! They have an all day brunch as well!

Have you been? Would you go?

26 days, 5 countries, 10 cities. 

So much food and several experiences that are now beautiful memories. Expect content of my recent Euro Trip, which will include where I ate 😏

This trip was over a year in the making for my friend’s wedding but decided to extend it in order to visit old friends, re-explore some places where I used to live, and explore new cities as well. 

In the end, it became an experience that reminded me just how lucky I am to have amazing people in my life and just how much I love exploring. I’ve always been a curious person but going to new places really sparks that curiosity even more. I love learning about the history, the culture now and of course, the food. 

But what makes any special are the people and the people on this trip really helped make this holiday one to remember ❤️

@cariocabowls goes beyond just the açai. (Get 20% off a Classic Carioca Bowl by showing this video)

I got to go with owner, Rich, to the Lake Oswego Farmers Market to learn more about how they connect in our community. A big thing I learned is that it’s about supporting each other and especially other local businesses.

By working with others who are also offering quality, crafted foods, Carioca Bowls creates bowls made with toppings by local makers in order to provide unique offerings that highlight many culinary delights from the PNW.

On a personal level, one of my most favorite parts of going to the farmers market is not only connecting with the owners but also learning about the passion that goes into each product, which makes me more eager to buy and support. What makes it even better is that it’s local.

It was an exciting experience to see from the business side how it works connecting with others in order to create collaborations that benefits everyone.

You get a little taste of South America at @titasjuicebar in Portland, Oregon.

An easy vegan pumpkin protein pancake that is soft, moist, and oh so flavorful!

Recipe:
1 cup all purpose flour 
1 TBSP baking powder
1/4 tsp salt
3 TBSP maple syrup 
1 vegan egg (preferably Bob’s Red Mill)
1/3 cup pumpkin purée 
3/4 cup oat milk or other milk 
1 TBSP olive oil
1 scoop of pumpkin pie spice protein powder by Truvani (you can omit the protein powder and add an extra 1/4 cup of flour and add 1 tsp pumpkin pie spice instead)

First mix dry ingredients together in a bowl. Then add wet ingredients.
Add a scoop of batter to heated pan and flip once pancake bubbles.

Top with your favorite topppings.

Enjoy!

Introducing Festive Delights: Vegan Ventures’ Champurrado Loaded Cookie and Ponche Special only at @sinfulconfectionsbakery from December 5th to December 31st! 🙌🏼

Growing up, one of my favorite drinks around the holidays was a champurrado. When I’d go to Tijuana, Mexico for Christmas to celebrate with my family. One of my tias (aunts) would always make a hot champurrado, which consists of Mexican chocolate, cinnamon, spices, and masa. 

For this month, I’ve partnered with Julie from @sinfulconfectionsbakery to transform this drink into a loaded cookie. Since I grew up here in Portland, Oregon, another favorite dessert of mine is a classic cookie so we wanted to combine both of my favorite treats together that are vegan and also, gluten-free!

You can enjoy this champurrado loaded cookie along with another favorite Mexican drink of mine: ponche (a hot Mexican fruit punch made with apples, hawthorn, oranges, guavas, pineapple, plum, raisins and spices such as cinnamon, cloves, hibiscus, anise, and Piloncillo
) from December 5th to December 31st! 

$6 for the champurrado loaded cookie and $5 for 12 oz. of ponche! 
Or get both for $10 and save $1! 

For $1 of every item sold, Sinful Confections will match that in order to donate to @xceleratewomen A Portland organization that helps women business owners grow their business and overcome business inequities.

Quick and easy vegan broccoli soup with @leafsup.packs owner, Keilah! Code: VENTURES10 for 10% off when you shop online #ad there’s also FREE local delivery 

Keilah started Leafsup packs as an easy way to get your daily greens that are versatile! It’s a frozen blend of parsley, mint, kale, broccoli, and spinach. You can use Leafsup to make not only juices and smoothies but also, sauces, cookies, pancakes, and of course, soup! 

For the vegan broccoli soup, here’s the recipe:

1 pack of @leafsup.packs thawed
1 large head of broccoli, chopped into florets
1 medium onion, chopped
3 cloves of garlic, minced
4 cups of vegetable broth
1 cup raw cashews, soaked in water for at least 2 hours
1 tbsp olive oil
Salt and pepper to taste

In a large pot, heat the olive oil over medium heat. Add the chopped onion and minced garlic and cook until the onion is translucent, about 5 minutes. 

Add the chopped broccoli to the pot and stir to combine with the onion mixture. Cook for another 5 minutes, until the broccoli begins to soften.

Pour in the vegetable broth and bring the mixture to a boil. Reduce heat to low and let the soup simmer for about 10 minutes, until the broccoli is fully cooked.

Drain the soaked cashews and add them to a blender along with 1 cup of water. Blend until the mixture is smooth and creamy.

Enjoy! What would you make with Leafsup?!

#easyvegansoup #easysouprecipe #healthysouprecipe #lunchideas #vegandinnerideas #pdxvegan #portlandvegan

Happy New Year and thank you for 4 years of Vegan Ventures!

4 years ago today I posted this photo (photo 1) to create Vegan Ventures. It started as a fun way to share my favorite recommendations. 

I never thought in my wildest dreams that this page would grow to what it is now. An incredible community but also, a way to explore my skills as a creative. This page has allowed me to not just share recommendations and story tell but also, has given me opportunities to work as a branding photographer, videographer, producer, digital marketer, this list goes on and I’ve been lucky enough to be able to work with incredible people using my skills, but it’s all honestly thanks to this page. I wouldn’t have connected with the people that I have without Vegan Ventures.

I came back to Portland May 2019 with the thought I’d be back temporarily to visit friends and family but time went on and I had to find out what I wanted to do with my life. I honestly felt lost for the longest time. This page what started as a hobby has given me purpose and so much joy and I am so grateful to have you here. 

It wasn’t until time last year I decided to go into my business full time. I feel blessed that this is what I get to do. To work with incredible people and help showcase what they do while getting to be creative.

It’s been a difficult road with hurdles and setbacks I’ve had to go through and I’d be lying if I didn’t say that there’s been many times I’ve thought about quitting. But your kind words of support and ongoing impact keeps me going.

Thank you for being here. 2024 there’s going to be more from Vegan Ventures with not just content but also, in person experiences such as my first international trip to Bali and other events in the works.
